Comment: All mainline up to here, even though ... Nxd4 is not the best move, according to "The Complete Vienna" by Tseitlin and Glazkov.  That book recommends ...Bb4+, which is much more disruptive.  This is just slightly better for White here.

This move is just fundamentally wrong.  Even if Black didn't particularly like it, he had to play ...Nxf3, since retreating into the path of the mobile center pawns is such a dismal option.  That Knight will have no future after d4.

Also wrong... Here, he just needed to play Be7 and get out of the center quickly.  By playing ...Bg4, he alerted me to a common theme in King Pawn openings... the Bc4-f7, Ng5+ (or Ne5+, depending) tactic to take advantage of an unprotected Bishop on g4.

It looks as if he's finally trying to castle and, once he does that, we'll only have a moderately better game for White.  Let's go for more by keeping him in the center!  This next move only took a bit of calculation, since it was mainly an intuitive sacrifice.

It looks as if he's finally trying to castle and, once he does that, we'll only have a moderately better game for White.  Let's go for more by keeping him in the center!  This next move only took a bit of calculation, since it was mainly an intuitive sacrifice.

It's easier to see the compensation for the sacrifice after the Knight moves.  Basically, the motivation was:

1.  Eliminate light squared bishop to weaken his light squares.
2.  Bring rook to open f file.
3.  Use advanced center pawns and develop quicker than opponent.

Being down a piece in this position is a decision that I think just about anyone would make.  :-)
